  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Overnight at Galsan
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Last night I walked upon the moon at Naong Tower,
    Today I shelter from the rain at Galsan's mouth.
    The falling light of the western river shoots like golden arrows,
    The angry clouds of the eastern peaks lie down like twin hounds.
    Cormorants stand at the fishing rocks, peering for their prey,
    But human voices and the boat's passing startle them into flight.
    In pairs they vanish into the mists,
    While I, alas, have not your keen eye to see them go.
  footnotes:
    - 'Naong Tower (懶翁塔): A Buddhist temple or pagoda associated with the lazy monk, suggesting a previous night''s spiritual wandering.'
    - The golden arrows and twin hounds are vivid natural imagery comparing the sunset and clouds to weapons and animals—a technique characteristic of classical Korean-Chinese poetry.
    - The cormorants represent a moment of natural grace that slips away, mirroring the speaker's reflective mood and inability to fully grasp fleeting beauty.
